        </p>
        
      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-sets-functions"><title>Useful tools on sets and functions</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-sets"><title>Properties of Sets</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.1"><title>Distributive laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A ∩ (∪_α B_α) = ∪_α(A ∩ B_α)</m> and <m>A ∪ (∩_α B_α) = ∩_α(A ∪ B_α)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.2"><title>De Morgan's laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A - (∪_α B_α) = ∩_α(A - B_α)</m> and <m>A - (∩_α B_α) = ∪_α(A - B_α)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <p>
            Template to prove two sets are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.3"><title>Power Set</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The <em>power set</em> <m>𝒫(S)</m> of a set <m>S</m> is the set of all subsets of <m>S</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Discussion of standard mathematical conventions for notation
            Notation for indices: <m>i,j,k,m,n</m> for finite or countably many indices, <m>α,β,...</m> for arbitrarily many indices.
            Notation for sets, elements of sets, and sets of sets: Small letters <m>a,b,c,p,q,x,y,z</m> for elements of sets, capital letters <m>A,B,C,X,Y,Z</m> for sets, calligraphic capital letters <m>ℬ,𝒞,𝒯,𝒰</m> for collections of sets.
          </p>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-functions"><title>Properties of functions</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For a function <m>f: G → H</m>, the set <m>G</m> is the <em>domain</em>, the set <m>H</m> is the <em>codomain</em>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Template to define a function
          </p>

          <p>
            Template to prove two functions are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A function <m>f: G → H</m> is <em>well-defined</em> if whenever <m>g,g' ∈ G</m> and <m>g = g'</m>, then <m>f(g) = f(g')</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              All functions are well-defined.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.8">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X → Y</m> be a function.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>one-to-one</em> (also called an <em>injection</em> and denoted <m>f: X ↪ Y</m>) if whenever <m>x,x' ∈ X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x = x'</m>.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>onto</em> (also called a <em>surjection</em> and denoted <m>f: X ↠ Y</m>) if for every <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m>, there is an <m>x</m> in <m>X</m> with <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                The function <m>f</m> is a <em>bijection</em> if <m>f</m> is both one-to-one and onto.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>invertible</em> if there is a function <m>g:Y → X</m> such that <m>f ∘ g = 1_Y</m> and <m>g ∘ f = 1_X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.9">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>a: G → H, b: H → K</m>, and <m>c: K → L</m> be functions. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are one-to-one then ba is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is one-to-one then a is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are onto then <m>ba</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is onto then <m>b</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>a</m> is a bijection if and only if <m>a</m> is invertible.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X → Y</m> be a function.
                The <em>image</em> of a subset <m>A</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>f(A) := \{f(a) | a ∈ A\}</m>.
                The <em>preimage</em> of a subset <m>B</m> of <m>Y</m> is <m>f\inv(B) := \{g | g ∈ X and f(g) ∈ B\}</m>.
                The <em>image</em> of <m>f</m> is <m>f(X)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-pan"><title>PAN = <q>Preimages are nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X → Y</m>, <m>E ⊆ E' ⊆ Y</m>, and <m>E_α ⊆ Y</m> for all <m>α</m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E) ⊆ f\inv(E')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(∪_α Eα) = ∪_αf\inv(E_α)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(∩α E_α) = ∩_αf\inv(E_α)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E' - E) = f\inv(E') - f\inv(E)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-iasn"><title>IASN = <q>Images are sometimes nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X → Y, C ⊆ C' ⊆ X</m>, and <m>Cα ⊆ X for all α</m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C) ⊆ f(C')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(∪α Cα) = ∪α f(Cα)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(∩α Cα) ⊆ ∩α f(Cα)</m>. If moreover <m>f</m> is injective, then <m>f(∩α Cα) = ∩α f(Cα)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C' - C) ⊇ f(C') - f(C)</m>. If moreover f is injective, then <m>f(C' - C) = f(C') - f(C)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.13">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X → Y</m>. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>A ⊆ X</m>, then <m>A ⊆ f\inv(f(A))</m>; if moreover <m>f</m> is injective then <m>A = f\inv(f(A))</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>B ⊆ Y</m> then <m>f(f\inv(B)) ⊆ B</m>; if moreover <m>f</m> is surjective then <m>f(f\inv(B)) = B</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-constructions"><title>Constructions of new sets from old ones, and the associated functions</title>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subsets"><title>Subsets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.15">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A</m> be a set. A <em>subset</em> of <m>A</m> is a set of some (possibly none, possibly all, possibly neither) of the elements of <m>A</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.16">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>B ⊆ A</m>. The <em>inclusion map</em> is the function <m>i:B → A</m> defined by <m>i(b) = b</m> for all <m>b ∈ B</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.17">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>B ⊆ A</m> and <m>i:B → A</m> is the inclusion, then <m>i</m> is an injection.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-products"><title>Product sets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.20">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A, B</m>, and <m>A_α</m> for all <m>α ∈ J</m> be sets. The <em>Cartesian product</em> <m>A × B := \{(a,b) | a ∈ A, b ∈ B\} and ∏α ∈ J A_α := \{(a_α)_{α ∈ J} | a_α ∈ A_α\}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.21">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_α</m> for all <m>α ∈ J</m> be sets and let <m>β</m> in <m>J</m>. The <em>projection map</em> <m>p_β: ∏_{α ∈ J} A_α → A_β</m> is defined by <m>p_β((a_α)_{α ∈ J}) = a_β for all (a_α)_{α ∈ J} ∈ ∏_{α ∈ J} A_α</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.22">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_α</m> for all <m>α ∈ J</m> be sets, let <m>β ∈ J</m>, and for each <m>α ∈ J - \{β\}</m>, let <m>b_α ∈ A_α</m>. The associated <em>product inclusion map</em> <m>i_β: A_β → ∏_{α ∈ J} A_α</m> is defined for each <m>a ∈ A_β</m> by <m>i_β(a) := (a_α)_{α ∈ J}</m>, where <m>a_β := a</m> and <m>a_α := b_α for all α ∈ J - \{β\}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.23">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Projection maps are surjections. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Product inclusion maps are injections.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-1.24">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>A ⊆ G</m> and <m>B ⊆ H</m>, then <m>A × B ⊆ G × H</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>

            <axiom xml:id="axiom-choice">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Axiom of Choice: If <m>Aα ≠ ∅</m> for all <m>α ∈ J</m>, then <m>∏α ∈ J Aα ≠ ∅</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </axiom>
            
          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quotients"><title>Quotient sets and equivalence relations</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.27">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  An <em>equivalence relation</em> <m>∼</m> on a set <m>X</m> is a subset <m>S</m> of <m>X × X</m> (where <m>(a,b) ∈ S</m> is written <m>a ∼ b</m>) that satisfies the following for all <m>a,b,c</m> in <m>X</m>: 
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ∼ a</m> (reflexive),
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ∼ b</m> implies <m>b ∼ a</m> (symmetric), and 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ∼ b</m> and <m>b ∼ c</m> implies <m>a ∼ c</m> (transitive).
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  The <em>equivalence class</em> of an element <m>a</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>[a] := \{b | b ∼ a\}</m>.
                  The notation <m>X/∼</m> denotes the set of equivalence classes, also called the <em>quotient</em> of <m>X</m> with respect to <m>∼</m>.
                  The function <m>q:X → X/∼</m> defined by <m>q(p) := [p]</m> for all <m>p ∈ X</m> is called the <em>equivalence map</em>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.28">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A <em>partition</em> of a set <m>X</m> is a collection of nonempty disjoint subsets of <m>X</m> whose union is <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.29">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set. 
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>∼</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>G</m>, then <m>X/∼</m> is a partition of <m>X</m>. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>𝒞</m> is a partition of <m>X</m>, and <m>T = \{(x,y) ∈ X × X | x,y are in the same element of 𝒞\}</m>, then <m>T</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.30">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>f: X → Y</m> be a function, and let <m>∼ = \{(p,p') ∈ X × X | f(p) = f(p')\}</m>. Then <m>∼</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.31"><title>FBT = Function Building Theorem for quotient sets</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>∼</m> be an equivalence relation on a set <m>X</m>, and let <m>f: X → Y</m> be a function satisfying the property that whenever <m>x,x' ∈ X</m> and <m>x ∼ x'</m> then <m>f(x) = f(x')</m>. Then:
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        There is a well-defined function <m>g:X/∼ → Y</m> defined by <m>g([x]) = f(x)</m> for all <m>[x]</m> in <m>X/∼</m>; that is, <m>g ∘ q = f</m>, where <m>q</m> is the equivalence map.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is onto, then <m>g</m> is onto.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> also satisfies the property that whenever <m>x,x' ∈ X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x ∼ x'</m>, then <m>g</m> is one-to-one.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <p>
              Template for proving a well-defined function with domain <m>X/∼</m>.
            </p>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.32">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set and let <m>S</m> be a subset of <m>X × X</m>. The <em>equivalence relation on <m>X</m> generated by</em> <m>S</m> is the intersection of all of the equivalence relations on <m>X</m> that contain <m>S</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
          </subsubsection>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-cardinality"><title>Cardinality</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.34">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A set <m>X</m> is <em>finite</em> if there is a bijection <m>X → \{1,...,n\}</m> for some natural number <m>n</m>, or <m>X</m> is empty. In this case the number <m>n</m> is called the <em>cardinality</em> of <m>X</m>.
                A set <m>X</m> is <em>infinite</em> if <m>X</m> is not finite. A set <m>X</m> is <em>countable</em> if there is an injection <m>X ↪ ℕ</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.35">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a set.
                (1) The following are equivalent: 
                  (1a) <m>X</m> is finite. 
                  (1b) There is an onto function <m>\{1,...,n\} ↠ X</m> for some <m>n ∈ ℕ</m>. 
                  (1c) There is a one-to-one function <m>X ↪ \{1,...,n\}</m> for some <m>n ∈ ℕ</m>.
                (2) The following are equivalent: 
                  (2a) <m>X</m> is infinite. 
                  (2b) There is an onto function <m>X ↠ ℕ</m>. 
                  (2c) There is a one-to-one function <m>ℕ ↪ X</m>.
                (3) The following are equivalent: 
                  (3a) <m>X</m> is countable. 
                  (3b) There is an onto function <m>ℕ → X</m>. 
                  (3c) There is an injection <m>X ↪ ℕ</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.36">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of finite sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, finite unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of countable sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, countable unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>
                    
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-bounds"><title>Upper and lower bound properties of ℕ and ℝ</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.39">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      An <em>upper bound</em> for a subset <m>A ⊆ ℝ</m> is a real number <m>r ∈ ℝ</m> satisfying <m>a ≤ r</m> for all <m>a ∈ A</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A <em>lower bound</em> for a subset <m>A ⊆ ℝ</m> is a real number <m>s ∈ ℝ</m> satisfying <m>s ≤ a</m> for all <m>a ∈ A</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Least upper bound property of <m>ℝ</m>): If <m>A ⊆ ℝ</m> and <m>A</m> has an upper bound, then <m>A</m> has a least upper bound. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Greatest lower bound property of <m>ℝ</m>): If <m>A ⊆ ℝ</m> and <m>A</m> has a lower bound, then <m>A</m> has a greatest lower bound.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.41">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (Archimedean property of <m>ℕ</m>): <m>ℕ</m> has no upper bound in <m>ℝ</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>
        
      </section>
      
